Featured Stories

Wind Tops Coal in US Electricity

Yousaff Habib

On April 14th, the U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA) revealed that for the first time ever, wind-powered electricity generation had exceeded both coal and nuclear power generation. While wind generation has exceeded nuclear power and coal-generated electricity separately in the past, this marks the first occasion that both have been surpassed simultaneously.

This landmark comes amid Biden’s lofty Clean Energy Plan, which includes a pledge to build a carbon-free grid by 2035, while investing $2 trillion towards an “equitable clean energy future.”

A number of factors played a role in this historic moment:

  • Waning Power Demand: Generally, during fall and spring months, the demand for power is decreased. Subsequently, many generators reduce their outputs, or use this time to undergo maintenance;
  • Surge in Wind Output: March is generally one of the windiest months, and the window in which wind generated electricity overtook coal and nuclear had extremely high wind speeds in the Southwest Power Pool (Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota, and neighboring states); and
  • Demand Matching: Since renewable energy has zero fuel costs, it is prioritized in most electricity systems. In times of low demand, this leaves less market space for other sources of electricity.

See also: EIA Electricity Generation Hourly Monitor

Canada’s Energy Transition Plans

Marc Vermette

Solar panel installation, image courtesy of MariaGodfrida/Pixabay


Experts say upgrading Canada’s entire energy infrastructure in a short period of time will be a technical challenge that will cost upwards of hundreds of billions of dollars.

The federal government has laid out an ambitious roadmap, consisting of:

  • carbon capture
  • hydrogen development
  • rapid electrification of transportation systems
  • accelerated sustainable energy roll-out, including:
    • wind power
    • solar power

This is to get Canada to its climate target of cutting emissions by 40%, or below 2005 levels, by 2030, and net-zero emissions by 2050.

“Very few people are stepping up to attempt to stop this,” says Donna Kennedy-Glans, regarding large-scale renewable energy projects around the country.

Canada’s Planned Energy Export Expansion

Marc Vermette

Ocean Falls Dam, British Columbia, image courtesy of A.Davey/Flickr CC


Hydro-Québec, Canada’s leading supplier of clean energy to the United States, has new plans to supply 1,250 megawatts of hydroelectric electricity to New York City.

The Champlain Hudson Power Express underground route, created to facilitate this supply, is scheduled to open in 2025.

Over a 25-year period, the export value of Canadian energy is estimated to exceed $20 billion.

Canada is already more than 80% clean (as opposed to the US’s 40%), owing primarily to:

  • hydroelectric energy
  • nuclear power

Last year, Canada exported 60.3 terawatt hours of power, a 50 percent increase over 2010 and four times the amount exported in 1990.

The exports, which account for around a tenth of the electricity generated in Canada, amount to barely a few of percentage points of US consumption.

Every bit helps to “green” US electricity, and bolster Canada’s economic bottom line.


Syncrude’s Mildred Lake oil sands mine, image courtesy of Syncrude Canada Ltd.


There are big environmental benefits, too, as the New York City deal will cut four megatonnes a year of emissions – the same as closing an oil sands mine.

Canada’s 2022 National Emissions Inventory

Andrew Leach


Canada’s National Inventory Report (NIR) and emissions projections (PDF) were released last week, and along with the Emissions Reduction Plan (ERP) released a week earlier, dramatically updates the picture we have of Canada’s emissions through the first months of the COVID pandemic, and also gives us a sense of just how far we have to go to meet our targets. I’ve updated most of my NIR data page which gives you a group of data visualizations you are more than welcome to use. I hope you enjoy it.
